  ('Single-Leg Glute Bridge Iso Hold', 'single-leg-glute-bridge-iso-hold', 'Single-Leg Glute Bridge Iso Hold is an isometric exercise using the single-leg bridge top hold to develop hip, core, spine control, tissue tolerance, and force expression without visible joint movement.', 'BEGINNER', 8, 2, NULL, 12, 45, 57, 'Single-leg bridge hold that trains hip extension, pelvis control, and posterior-chain endurance without spinal motion.', 'Primary subrole: trunk_pelvis_anti_movement_control. Coach exact joint angles, gradual tension, steady breathing, and a clean stop. Isometrics are useful only when the athlete owns the position rather than surviving the clock.', 'Own the position, build steady pressure, breathe, and stop before the shape changes.', 'Single-leg hip-extension isometric', 'resilience', 'trunk_pelvis_anti_movement_control', 'single_leg_bridge_pelvis_control_hold', '{"primary_joint_actions":["hip_extension_isometric","pelvic_anti_rotation","knee_flexion_hold","spine_neutral_control"],"primary_tissues":["glutes","hamstrings","anterior_core","hip_flexors"],"primary_motor_control_demands":["single_leg_pelvis_control","hip_extension_without_rotation","brace_under_unilateral_load"],"postural_shape":"single-leg bridge top hold","breathing_demand":"steady breathing at top position","balance_demand":"moderate supine unilateral","coordination_demand":"moderate","impact_level":0}'::jsonb, '{"movement_description":"Set up in the single-leg bridge top hold. Create tension gradually, hold the exact position, breathe under control, and end the set before posture, pain-free range, or breathing quality breaks.","setup":["Set the athlete in the single-leg bridge top hold.","Choose the easiest variation that allows pain-free alignment and calm breathing.","Coach a gradual build of tension instead of a sudden jerk into the position."],"execution_steps":["Create the target body shape and confirm the key joints are aligned.","Build pressure into the floor, implement, wall, ban