  ('Tibialis Raise Iso Hold', 'tibialis-raise-iso-hold', 'Tibialis Raise Iso Hold is an isometric exercise using the standing wall-supported toe-up hold to develop ankle, shin, foot control, tissue tolerance, and force expression without visible joint movement.', 'BEGINNER', 8, 2, NULL, 15, 45, 60, 'Toe-up shin hold that builds dorsiflexor capacity and lower-leg control for running, landing, and deceleration.', 'Primary subrole: slow_eccentric_isometric_joint_resilience. Coach exact joint angles, gradual tension, steady breathing, and a clean stop. Isometrics are useful only when the athlete owns the position rather than surviving the clock.', 'Own the position, build steady pressure, breathe, and stop before the shape changes.', 'Dorsiflexor isometric', 'resilience', 'slow_eccentric_isometric_joint_resilience', 'tibialis_raise_iso_hold', '{"primary_joint_actions":["ankle_dorsiflexion_isometric","knee_extension_hold","foot_control","toe_extension_hold"],"primary_tissues":["tibialis_anterior","foot_intrinsics","calves","peroneals"],"primary_motor_control_demands":["dorsiflexion_tension","shin_control","heel_pressure"],"postural_shape":"standing wall-supported toe-up hold","breathing_demand":"normal breathing","balance_demand":"stable wall support","coordination_demand":"low","impact_level":0}'::jsonb, '{"movement_description":"Set up in the standing wall-supported toe-up hold. Create tension gradually, hold the exact position, breathe under control, and end the set before posture, pain-free range, or breathing quality breaks.","setup":["Set the athlete in the standing wall-supported toe-up hold.","Choose the easiest variation that allows pain-free alignment and calm breathing.","Coach a gradual build of tension instead of a sudden jerk into the position."],"execution_steps":["Create the target body shape and confirm the key joints are aligned.","Build pressure into the floor, implement, wall, band, cable, bar, or body position as appropriate.","Hold for about 15 seco