  ('Big Toe Press Iso Hold', 'big-toe-press-iso-hold', 'Big Toe Press Iso Hold is an isometric exercise using the standing or seated big-toe press hold to develop foot, ankle, calf control, tissue tolerance, and force expression without visible joint movement.', 'BEGINNER', 8, 2, NULL, 8, 20, 28, 'Big-toe pressure hold that activates the arch and foot intrinsics for sprinting, jumping, and cutting positions.', 'Primary subrole: activate. Coach exact joint angles, gradual tension, steady breathing, and a clean stop. Isometrics are useful only when the athlete owns the position rather than surviving the clock.', 'Own the position, build steady pressure, breathe, and stop before the shape changes.', 'Hallux and arch activation isometric', 'prepare_and_access', 'activate', 'big_toe_press_activation_hold', '{"primary_joint_actions":["hallux_flexion_isometric","arch_control","ankle_neutral_hold","toe_dissociation"],"primary_tissues":["foot_intrinsics","flexor_hallucis_longus","calves","plantar_fascia"],"primary_motor_control_demands":["big_toe_pressure","arch_stiffness","toe_relaxation_except_target"],"postural_shape":"standing or seated big-toe press hold","breathing_demand":"normal breathing","balance_demand":"stable seated or standing","coordination_demand":"low to moderate toe control","impact_level":0}'::jsonb, '{"movement_description":"Set up in the standing or seated big-toe press hold. Create tension gradually, hold the exact position, breathe under control, and end the set before posture, pain-free range, or breathing quality breaks.","setup":["Set the athlete in the standing or seated big-toe press hold.","Choose the easiest variation that allows pain-free alignment and calm breathing.","Coach a gradual build of tension instead of a sudden jerk into the position."],"execution_steps":["Create the target body shape and confirm the key joints are aligned.","Build pressure into the floor, implement, wall, band, cable, bar, or body position as appropriate.","Hold for