  ('Ring Row Top Iso Hold', 'ring-row-top-iso-hold', 'Ring Row Top Iso Hold is an isometric exercise using the inclined body row top hold to develop shoulder, elbow, forearm control, tissue tolerance, and force expression without visible joint movement.', 'BEGINNER', 8, 3, NULL, 10, 60, 70, 'Top-position suspended row hold that builds pulling strength, grip, and scapular control.', 'Primary subrole: pull_hang_grip_strength. Coach exact joint angles, gradual tension, steady breathing, and a clean stop. Isometrics are useful only when the athlete owns the position rather than surviving the clock.', 'Own the position, build steady pressure, breathe, and stop before the shape changes.', 'Horizontal pull top-position isometric', 'capacity', 'pull_hang_grip_strength', 'ring_row_top_iso_hold', '{"primary_joint_actions":["elbow_flexion_isometric","shoulder_extension_hold","scapular_retraction_depression","spine_anti_extension"],"primary_tissues":["lats","rhomboids","middle_traps","biceps","forearm_flexors"],"primary_motor_control_demands":["top_row_control","ring_stability","whole_body_line"],"postural_shape":"inclined body row top hold","breathing_demand":"steady breathing while holding chest to handles","balance_demand":"moderate suspended support","coordination_demand":"moderate","impact_level":0}'::jsonb, '{"movement_description":"Set up in the inclined body row top hold. Create tension gradually, hold the exact position, breathe under control, and end the set before posture, pain-free range, or breathing quality breaks.","setup":["Set the athlete in the inclined body row top hold.","Choose the easiest variation that allows pain-free alignment and calm breathing.","Coach a gradual build of tension instead of a sudden jerk into the position."],"execution_steps":["Create the target body shape and confirm the key joints are aligned.","Build pressure into the floor, implement, wall, band, cable, bar, or body position as appropriate.","Hold for about 10 seconds or the prescr