  'Isometrics without breath-holding contests or wrong phase intent',
  'Static holds, overcoming presses, and joint-angle isometrics must match phase intent — low-fatigue activation in Prepare & Access, shape ownership in Movement Intelligence, tissue tolerance in Resilience, and loaded bracing in Capacity — never fatigue finishers or max-effort holds before fresh Output.',
  'Isometrics cards span trunk anti-movement holds, lower-body joint-angle strength, foot-ankle resilience, upper-body support and overcoming presses, and loaded pin/rack isometrics for athletes building position ownership, tissue tolerance, and force at specific angles without visible movement.',
  'Isometric quality depends on exact joint angles, breathing, intent, and stop rules. Poor placement, breath-holding contests, or holds after fatigue steal from speed, skill, and neural output while raising blood-pressure and compensation risk.',
  'Scale by position quality first, then duration, then load or intent. Use Prepare & Access for activation and access; Movement Intelligence for shape holds; Resilience for anti-movement and tissue tolerance; Capacity for loaded overcoming isometrics with full rest.',
  'Do not turn holds into pain-tolerance or breath-holding contests; do not stack multiple high-intent isometrics before Output; do not program pin/rack isometrics without safe setup and supervision.'
)
